<h2 class=3D"sm:text-[2.625rem] text-[1.38rem] !leading-normal font-semibol=
d mb-2">MAC Address Format</h2>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2">MAC Addresses are written in the form of 12-digit strings that conta=
in hexadecimal numbers (0 =E2=80=93 9 and A =E2=80=93 F). The string is div=
ided into six groups of two letters each, and are separated by either colon=
, a hyphen, or a period. Sometimes, the address is in the form of a single =
string without any separation.&nbsp;</p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2">Each of these groups of two is known as an octet. Here is an example=
 of a MAC address:</p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2" style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong><span style=3D"color: #e03e2d;=
">BA-20-C1-AD-7D-6A</span></strong></p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2">The above mentioned address is in <strong>Hyphen-Hexadecimal notatio=
n</strong>. The other usually written formats are</p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2"><strong>Colon-Hexadecimal notation</strong> =3D <strong><span style=
=3D"color: #e03e2d;">BA:20:C1:AD:7D:6A</span></strong></p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2"><span style=3D"background-color: rgb(255 255 255 / var(--tw-bg-opaci=
ty));"><strong>Period-separated Hexadecimal notation</strong> =3D <strong><=
span style=3D"color: #e03e2d;">BA.20.C1.AD.7D.6A</span></strong></span></p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2"><span style=3D"background-color: rgb(255 255 255 / var(--tw-bg-opaci=
ty));">Sometimes, the MAC address is in the form of a single string without=
 any separation.&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"font-size: 1.25rem; background-=
color: rgb(255 255 255 / var(--tw-bg-opacity));"></span></p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2">Each of groups of two in MAC Address is known as an octet. The first=
 three octets (<strong><span style=3D"color: #e03e2d;">BA-20-C1</span></str=
ong>) of the MAC address are collectively known as the Organizationally Uni=
que Identifier (OUI). They are unique and specific to the manufacturer of t=
he Network Interface Card (NIC) that is present in a computer system.</p>
<p class=3D"sm:text-xl text-sm leading-[1.5rem] sm:leading-[2.2rem] sm:mt-3=
 mt-2">The last three octets (<strong><span style=3D"color: #e03e2d;">AD:7D=
:6A</span></strong>) of the MAC address are specific to the particular NIC =
of the device. They are the unique identifier of the device itself. The las=
t part is different in every address.</p>
</div>
